# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dmx512-lighting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The purpose of architectural lighting design is to balance the characteristics of light within a space to optimize the technical, visual, and, most recently, the non-visual components of ergonomics with respect to the illumination of buildings and spaces.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The technical requirements include the amount of light needed to perform a task, the energy consumed by the lighting within a space and the relative distribution and direction of light so as not to cause unnecessary glare or discomfort.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] As part of the lighting design process, both cultural and contextual factors also need to be considered.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For example, bright lighting was a mark of wealth through much of Chinese history, but uncontrolled bright light is known to be detrimental to insects, birds, and the visibility of stars.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The history of electric light is well documented, and with the developments in lighting technology the profession of lighting developed alongside it.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The development of high-efficiency, low-cost fluorescent lamps led to a reliance on electric light and a uniform blanket approach to lighting, but the energy crisis of the 1970s required more design consideration and reinvigorated the use of daylight.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The New York-based Illuminating Engineering Society (IES) was formed in 1906.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] A London-based organization established in 1909 with the same name is now known as the Society of Light and Lighting (SLL), a part of CIBSE.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The International Commission on Illumination (CIE) was established in 1913.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The Institution of Lighting Professionals was established as the Association of Public Lighting Engineers in 1924.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Around the world similar professional organizations evolved.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Initially, these industry organizations were primarily focused on the science and engineering of lighting rather than the aesthetic design, but in 1969 a group of designers established the International Association of Lighting Designers (IALD).
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] One of the earliest proponents of architectural lighting design was Richard Kelly who established his practice in 1935.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] While many architectural lighting designers have a background in electrical engineering, architectural engineering, architecture, or luminaire manufacturing, several universities and technical schools now offer degree programs specifically in architectural lighting design.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The process of architectural lighting design generally follows the architect's plan of works in terms of key project stages: feasibility, concept, detail, construction documentation, site supervision and commissioning.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] After the feasibility stage, where the parameters for the project are set, the concept stage is when the lighting design is developed in terms of lit effect, technical lighting targets and overall visual strategy usually using concept sketches, renderings, or mood boards.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The source for daylight or natural lighting is the sun.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Sunlight provides the greatest quality of light, rated 100 CRI, on the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] There are psychological and physical health benefits that come from using daylight in a space.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For example, it can help to ease seasonal affective disorder (SAD), it can provide people with the necessary vitamin D, and can assist in regulating circadian rhythms, or daily light and dark cycles.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Using daylight as a light source can eliminate the use of energy.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Daylighting can also cause deterioration of materials and finishes and an increased use of energy for cooling a space.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The architectural makeup of a space impacts the day lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] It can be used in a space through windows, openings of the interior, skylights, and reflective surfaces.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Electric lighting or artificial lighting is a type of architectural lighting that includes electric light sources.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The overall purpose of electric lighting is to allow the user of the space to see at various times in the day, but especially at night or in winter season, when daylight is no longer a possible or sufficient source of light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Artificial lighting helps to create or enhance the aesthetic of a space.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Various techniques can be implemented when it comes to electric lighting, since users have more control over the light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] This can include dimming or increasing the brightness of a lamp, diffusion of the light source, and the use of different lamp hues.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The main sources used for electric lighting include incandescent lamps, solid state lamps (LED, etc.), and gas discharge lamps.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Lighting fixtures come in a wide variety of styles for various functions.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The most important functions are as a holder for the light source, to provide directed light and to avoid visual glare.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Some are very plain and functional, while some are pieces of art in themselves.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Nearly any material can be used, so long as it can tolerate the excess heat and is in keeping with safety codes.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] An important property of light fixtures is the luminous efficacy or wall-plug efficiency, meaning the amount of usable light emanating from the fixture per used energy, usually measured in lumen per watt.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] A fixture using replaceable light sources can also have its efficiency quoted as the percentage of light passed from the "bulb" to the surroundings.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The more transparent the lighting fixture is, the higher efficacy.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Shading the light will normally decrease efficiency but increase the directionality and the visual comfort probability.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The PH-lamps are a series of light fixtures designed by Danish designer and writer Poul Henningsen from 1926 onwards.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The lamp is designed with multiple concentric shades to eliminate visual glare, only emitting reflected light, obscuring the light source.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Designers utilize the idea of lighting layers when creating a lighting plan for a space.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Lighting layers include: task layer, focal layer, ambient layer, decorative layer, and daylight layer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Each layer contributes a function to the space and often they work together to create a well composed lighting design.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The task layer is lighting that serves a purpose to perform a certain job or task.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Typically, in this layer, there tends to be a need for more light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] An example of this would be the use of under cabinet lighting in a kitchen.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The focal layer is when lighting is used to highlight a certain feature in a room, such as a fireplace.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] This type of lighting draws the eye to that certain area.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The ambient layer provides for background or general lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] This layer has a strong influence on the brightness of a space.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] In the decorative layer, lighting is used as an ornament to the space and can help develop the style.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The daylight layer uses natural light or the sun to light a space.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Using the layering technique helps to develop the aesthetic and functionality of lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Color temperature for white light sources also affects their use for certain applications.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The color temperature of a white light source is the temperature in kelvin of a theoretical black body emitter that most closely matches the spectral characteristics of the lamp.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Incandescent light bulbs have a color temperature around 2700 to 3000 kelvin; daylight is around 6500 kelvin.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Lower color temperature lamps have relatively more energy in the yellow and red part of the visible spectrum, while high color temperatures correspond to lamps with more of a blue-white appearance.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For critical inspection or color matching tasks, or for retail displays of food and clothing, the color temperature of the lamps will be selected for the best overall lighting effect.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Color may also be used for functional reasons.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For example, blue light makes it difficult to see veins and thus may be used to discourage drug use.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The correlated color temperature (CCT) of a light source is the temperature of an ideal black-body radiator that radiates light of comparable chromaticity to that of the light source.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Color temperature is a characteristic of visible light that has important applications in lighting, photography, videography, publishing, manufacturing, astrophysics, horticulture, and other fields.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Color temperature is conventionally stated in the SI unit of absolute temperature, the kelvin, having the unit symbol K.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For lighting building interiors, it is often important to take into account the color temperature of illumination.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For example, a warmer (i.e. lower color temperature) light is often used in public areas to promote relaxation, while a cooler (higher color temperature) light is used to enhance concentration in offices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] CCT dimming for LED technology is regarded as a difficult task, since binning, age and temperature drift effects of LEDs change the actual color value output.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Here feedback loop systems can be used for example with color sensors, to actively monitor and control the color output of multiple color mixing LEDs.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The color temperature of the electromagnetic radiation emitted from an ideal black body is defined as its surface temperature in Kelvin, or alternatively in *mireds* (micro-reciprocal kelvin).
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] This permits the definition of a standard by which light sources are compared.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For simple installations, hand-calculations based on tabular data can be used to provide an acceptable lighting design.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] More critical or optimized designs now routinely use mathematical modeling on a computer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Based on the positions and mounting heights of the fixtures, and their photometric characteristics, the proposed lighting layout can be checked for uniformity and quantity of illumination.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For larger projects or those with irregular floor plans, lighting design software can be used.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Each fixture has its location entered, and the reflectance of walls, ceiling, and floors can be entered.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The computer program will then produce a set of contour charts overlaid on the project floor plan, showing the light level to be expected at the working height.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] More advanced programs can include the effect of light from windows or skylights, allowing further optimization of the operating cost of the lighting installation.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The amount of daylight received in an internal space can typically be analyzed by undertaking a daylight factor calculation.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The IES zonal cavity method (also known as the lumen method) is used as a basis for both hand, tabulated, and computer calculations.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] This method uses the reflectance coefficients of room surfaces to model the contribution to useful illumination at the working level of the room due to light reflected from the walls and the ceiling.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Simplified photometric values are usually given by fixture manufacturers for use in this method.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Computer modeling of outdoor flood lighting usually proceeds directly from photometric data.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The total lighting power of a lamp is divided into small solid angular regions.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Each region is extended to the surface which is to be lit and the area calculated, giving the light power per unit of area.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Where multiple lamps are used to illuminate the same area, each one's contribution is summed.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Again the tabulated light levels (in lux or foot-candles) can be presented as contour lines of constant lighting value, overlaid on the project plan drawing.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Hand calculations might only be required at a few points, but computer calculations allow a better estimate of the uniformity and lighting level.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] products that are recessed into the ceiling, or sometimes for uplights placed on the floor.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The name comes from the shape of the housing.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The term "pot lights" is often used in Canada and parts of the US.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The protective housing is concealed behind a ceiling or wall, leaving only the fixture itself exposed.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The finished housing is exposed, not flush mount with surface.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Light is closely placed to wall, typically to enhance a textured surface.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The most efficient source of electric light is the low-pressure sodium lamp.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] It produces, for all practical purposes, a monochromatic yellow light, which gives a similarly monochromatic perception of any illuminated scene.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] For this reason, it is generally reserved for outdoor public lighting usages.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Low-pressure sodium lights are favored for public lighting by astronomers, since the light pollution that they generate can be easily filtered, contrary to broadband or continuous spectra.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The modern incandescent light bulb, with a coiled filament of tungsten, was commercialized in the 1920s developed from the carbon filament lamp introduced in about 1880.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] As well as bulbs for normal illumination, there is a very wide range, including low voltage, low-power types often used as components in equipment, but now largely displaced by LEDs.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Fluorescent lamps consist of a glass tube that contains mercury vapor or argon under low pressure.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Electricity flowing through the tube causes the gases to give off ultraviolet energy.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] The inside of the tubes are coated with phosphors that give off visible light when struck by ultraviolet energy.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Light-emitting diodes (LEDs) became widespread as indicator lights in the 1970s.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] With the invention of high-output LEDs by Shuji Nakamura, LEDs are now in use as solid-state lighting for general lighting applications.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Initially, due to relatively high cost per lumen, LED lighting was most used for lamp assemblies of under 10 W such as flashlights.
[src:dmx512-lighting/architectural-lighting-design] Development of higher-output lamps was motivated by programs such as the U.S.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 has also expanded to uses in non-theatrical interior and architectural lighting, at scales ranging from strings of Christmas lights to electronic billboards and stadium or arena concerts.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] It can now be used to control almost anything, reflecting its popularity in all types of venues.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 uses a unidirectional EIA-485 (RS-485) differential signaling at its physical layer, in conjunction with a variable-size, packet-based communication protocol.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 does not include automatic error checking and correction and therefore is not an appropriate control for hazardous applications, such as pyrotechnics or movement of theatrical rigging.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] However, it is still used for such applications.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] False triggering may be caused by electromagnetic interference, static electricity discharges, improper cable termination, excessively long cables, or poor quality cables.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The DMX standard is published by the Entertainment Services and Technology Association (ESTA), and can be downloaded from its website.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Developed by the Engineering Commission of United States Institute for Theatre Technology (USITT), the DMX512 standard (for digital multiplex with 512 pieces of information) was created in 1986, with subsequent revisions in 1990 leading to USITT DMX512/1990.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] In 1998, the ESTA began a revision process to develop the standard as an ANSI standard.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The resulting revised standard, known officially as "Entertainment Technology—USITT DMX512-A—Asynchronous Serial Digital Data Transmission Standard for Controlling Lighting Equipment and Accessories", was approved by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in November 2004.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] It was revised again in 2008, and is the current standard known as "E1.11 – 2008, USITT DMX512-A", or just "DMX512-A".
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A DMX512 network employs a multi-drop bus topology with nodes strung together in what is commonly called a daisy chain.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A network consists of a single DMX512 controller – which is the master of the network — and one or more slave devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] For example, a lighting console is frequently employed as the controller for a network of slave devices such as dimmers, fog machines and intelligent lights.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Each slave device has a DMX512 "IN" connector and usually an "OUT" (or "THRU") connector as well.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The controller, which usually has only an OUT connector, is connected via a DMX512 cable to the IN connector of the first slave.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A second cable then links the OUT or THRU connector of the first slave to the IN connector of the next slave in the chain, and so on.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] For example, the block diagram below shows a simple network consisting of a controller and three slaves.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The specification requires a 'terminator' to be connected to the final OUT or THRU connector of the last slave on the daisy chain, which would otherwise be unconnected.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A terminator is a stand-alone male connector with an integral 120 Ω resistor connected across the primary data signal pair; this resistor matches the cable's characteristic impedance.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] If a secondary data pair is used, a termination resistor is connected across it as well.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Although simple systems (i.e., systems having few devices and short cables) will sometimes function normally without a terminator, the standard requires its use.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Some DMX slave devices have built-in terminators that can be manually activated with a mechanical switch or by software, or by automatically sensing the absence of a connected cable.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A DMX512 network is called a "DMX universe".
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Each OUT connector on a DMX512 controller can control a single universe.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A DMX512 universe is made up of 512 channels, with each channel containing a value between 0 and 255.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Each slave device in the chain can "look at" a different set of channels in order to be controlled by the master controller.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Smaller controllers may have a single OUT connector, enabling them to control only one universe, whereas large control desks (operator consoles) may have the capacity to control multiple universes, with an OUT connector provided for each universe.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Many of the more modern control desks, instead of featuring multiple OUT connectors, have an unshielded twisted pair connector (such as Cat 5, Cat 5e or Cat 6).
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Such cables and systems can control up to 524,288 universes of DMX512 (32,768 subnets × 16 universes per subnet) using the Art-Net IV protocol, or 65,536 universes using the sACN protocol, and the existing Ethernet in buildings.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 data is transmitted over a differential pair using EIA-485 voltage levels.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 electrical specifications are identical to those of the EIA-485-A standard, except where stated otherwise in E1.11.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 is a bus network no more than 400 metres (1,300 ft) long, with not more than 32 unit loads (individual devices connected) on a single bus.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] If more than 32 unit loads need to communicate, the network can be expanded across parallel buses using DMX splitters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Network wiring consists of a shielded twisted pair, with a characteristic impedance of 120 Ω, with a termination resistor at the end of the cable furthest from the controller to absorb signal reflections.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 has two twisted pair data paths, although the specification currently only defines the use of one of the twisted pairs.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The second pair is undefined but required by the electrical specification.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The E1.11 (DMX512 2004) electrical specification addresses the connection of DMX512 signal common to earth ground.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Specifically, the standard recommends that transmitter ports (DMX512 controller OUT port) have a low impedance connection between signal common and ground; such ports are referred to as *grounded*.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] It is further recommended that receivers have a high-impedance connection between signal common and ground; such ports are referred to as *isolated*.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The standard also allows for isolated transmitter ports and non-isolated receivers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] It also recommends that systems ground the signal common at only one point, in order to avoid the formation of disruptive ground loops.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Grounded receivers that have a hard connection between signal common and ground are permitted, but their use is strongly discouraged.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Several possible grounding configurations that are commonly used with EIA-485 are specifically disallowed by E1.11.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The original DMX512 1990 specified that where connectors are used, the data link shall use five-pin XLR style electrical connectors (XLR-5), with female connectors used on transmitting (OUT) ports and male connectors on receiving ports.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The use of any other XLR-style connector is prohibited.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The three-pin XLR connector is commonly used for DMX512, on lighting and related control equipment, particularly at the budget/DJ end of the market.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] However, using three-pin XLR connectors for DMX512 is specifically prohibited by section 7.1.2 of the DMX512 standard.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Use of the three-pin XLR in this context firstly presents a risk of damage to the lighting equipment should an audio cable carrying 48-volt phantom power be accidentally connected.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Three-pin XLRs designed for audio applications, rather than DMX512 communications, may also lead to signal degradation and unreliable operation of the DMX network.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512-A (ANSI E1.11-2008) defined the use of eight-pin modular (8P8C, or "RJ-45") connectors for fixed installations where regular plugging and unplugging of equipment is not required.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Several manufacturers used other pinouts for RJ-45 connectors prior to this inclusion in the standard.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Other form factors of connectors are permitted on equipment where the XLR and RJ-45 would not fit or are considered inappropriate, for example, on equipment intended for permanent installation.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The 8P8C modular connector pinout matches the conductor pairing scheme used by Category 5 (Cat5) twisted pair patch cables.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The avoidance of pins 4 and 5 helps to prevent equipment damage if the cabling is accidentally plugged into a single-line public switched telephone network phone jack.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] In the early days of digital lighting control, equipment manufacturers employed various connectors and pinouts for their proprietary digital control signals.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The most common of these is the three-pin XLR connector.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] When DMX512 was ratified, many of these manufacturers then issued firmware updates to enable the use of DMX512 control on their existing equipment by the use of a simple adapter to and from the standard 5-pin XLR style connector.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] As the electrical specification currently only defines a purpose for a single wire pair, some equipment manufacturers continue to use it.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Such equipment is not compliant with the DMX standard, but may be sufficiently compatible for operation using simple adapters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] There is a risk of equipment damage if 3-pin XLR audio and DMX signals are plugged into each other.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Section 7 of ANSI E1.11 - 2008 prohibits the use of XLR-3 connectors with DMX512.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Since DMX512 over XLR-3 is not officially standardised, there may be devices that use other pinouts.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Color Kinetics has their own version of the RJ-45 connector for DMX, which predates the 2008 official inclusion in the DMX512 standard.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The standard cables used in DMX512 networks employ XLR5 connectors, with a male connector on one end and a female connector on the other end.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The cable's male connector attaches to the transmitting, female jack (OUT), and its female connector attaches to the receiving, male jack (IN).
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Cabling for DMX512 was removed from the ANSI E1.11 standard, and a separate cabling standards project was started in 2003.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Two cabling standards have been developed, one for portable DMX512 cables (ANSI E1.27-1 – 2006) and one for permanent installations (draft standard BSR E1.27-2).
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] This resolved issues arising from the differences in requirements for cables used in touring shows versus those used for permanent infrastructure.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The electrical characteristics of DMX512 cable are specified in terms of impedance and capacitance, although there are often mechanical and other considerations that must be considered as well.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Cable types that are appropriate for DMX512 usage will have a nominal characteristic impedance of 120 Ω.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Also, cables designed for EIA-485 typically meet the DMX512 electrical specifications.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Conversely, microphone and line-level audio cables lack the requisite electrical characteristics and thus are not suitable for DMX512 cabling.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The significantly lower impedance and higher capacitance of these cables distort the DMX512 digital waveforms, which in turn can cause irregular operation or intermittent errors that are difficult to identify and correct.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Cat5 cable, commonly used for networking and telecommunications, has been tested by ESTA for use with DMX512A.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] RJ45 connectors are used by some DMX-compatible hardware with ESTA standard or proprietary pinouts.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] At the data link layer, a DMX512 controller transmits asynchronous serial data at 250 kbit/s.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The data format is fixed at one start bit, eight data bits (least significant first), two stop bits and no parity.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The start of a packet is signified by a break followed by a "mark" (a logical one), known as the "Mark After Break" (MAB).
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The break, which signals the end of one packet and the start of another, causes receivers to start reception and also serves as a frame (position reference) for data bytes within the packet.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Following the break, up to 513 slots are sent.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The first slot is reserved for a "Start Code" that specifies the type of data in the packet.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A start code of 0x00 (hexadecimal zero) is the standard value used for all DMX512 compatible devices, which includes most lighting fixtures and dimmers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Other start codes are used for Text packets (0x17), System Information Packets (0xCF), for the RDM extension to DMX (0xCC), and various proprietary systems.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] ESTA maintains a database of alternate start codes.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] All slots following the start code contain control settings for slave devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A slot's position within the packet determines the device and function to be controlled, while its data value specifies the control set point.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512 timing parameters may vary over a wide range.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The original authors specified the standard this way to provide the greatest design flexibility.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Because of this, however, it was difficult to design receivers that operated over the entire timing range.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] As a result of this difficulty, the timing specification of the original 1986 standard was changed in 1990.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Specifically, the MAB, which was originally fixed at 4 μs, was changed to 8 μs, minimum.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The E1.11 (2004) standard relaxed the transmitter and receiver timing specifications.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] This relaxed the timing requirements for systems using controllers built to DMX512-A (E1.11); however, a significant number of legacy devices still employ transmit timing near the minimum end of the range.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Maximum times are not specified because, as long as a packet is sent at least once per second, the BREAK, MAB, inter-slot time, and the mark between the last slot of the packet and the break (MBB) can be as long as desired.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] A maximum-sized packet, which has 512 *channels* (slots following the start code), takes approximately 23 ms to send, corresponding to a maximum refresh rate of about 44 Hz.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] For higher refresh rates, packets having fewer than 512 channels can be sent.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The standard does not specify the minimum number of slots that can be sent in a packet.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] However, it does require that packets be transmitted so that the leading edges of any two sequential BREAKs must be separated by at least 1204 μs, and receivers must be able to handle packets with break-to-break times as short as 1196 μs.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The minimum break-to-break transmit time can be achieved by sending packets that contain at least 24 slots (by adding extra padding bytes, if necessary) or by stretching parameters such as the BREAK, MAB, Interslot, or Interpacket times.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Most data is sent with the default Null Start Code of 00h.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Dimmer packs or racks use a group of slots to determine the levels for their dimmers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Typically, a dimmer has a starting address that represents the lowest-numbered dimmer in that pack, and the addressing increases from there to the highest-numbered dimmer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] As an example, for two packs of six dimmers each, the first pack would start at address 1 and the second pack at address 7.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Each slot in the DMX512 packet corresponds to one dimmer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX does not mandate a method of 16-bit encoding for Null Start Code packets; however, many parameters of moving lights make use of encoding larger than 8-bit numbers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] To control these parameters more accurately, some fixtures use two channels for parameters that require greater accuracy.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The first of the two channels controls the coarse (256 steps for the whole range of movement) and the second controls the fine (256 steps for each coarse step).
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] This gives a 16-bit value range of 65536 steps, permitting much greater accuracy for any 16-bit controlled parameter such as Pan or Tilt.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512's popularity is partly due to its robustness.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The cable can be abused without any loss of function in ways that would render Ethernet or other high-speed data cables useless, although cable faults can occasionally lead to intermittent problems such as random triggering.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Unexpected fixture behavior is caused by addressing errors, cable faults, incorrect data from the controller, or multiple DMX sources inadvertently applied to a single chain of fixtures.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] In the 1986 and 1990 standards, the use of the second data pair is not defined other than as an ‘optional second data link’.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Both unidirectional and bidirectional use were envisioned.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Other proprietary uses have been implemented for these pins.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Schemes that use voltage outside of the range allowed by EIA-485 are disallowed.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Guidance on allowed usage can be found in Annex B of E1.11.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Current standard practice is to leave the secondary data link pins unused.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512-A specifies that the connector must be a five-pin XLR connector.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] DMX512-A uses a single pair of conductors, so it can be connected using the cheaper 3-pin XLR connectors.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Some manufacturers made units with three-pin XLR connectors because of their lower cost.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] However, as 3-pin XLRs are commonly used for connecting microphones and sound mixing consoles, there is a risk of wrongly connecting DMX512 equipment to microphones and other sound equipment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The +48 volt phantom power emitted by mixing consoles could damage DMX512 equipment if connected to it.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The DMX512 signals emitted by lighting desks can damage microphones and other sound equipment if connected to it.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] As a result, the best practice is to use only 5-pin XLRs for DMX512 signals, to avoid the risk of confusion with connectors used for sound signals.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The DMX512 signal lines require a single 120 Ω termination resistor to be fitted at the extreme end of the signal cable.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Some of the more common symptoms of improper termination are flashing, uncontrollable or incorrect light operation, or other undesired random special effects.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Some equipment has automatic termination, others a physical switch, while the remainder requires a physical terminator (e.g. male XLR-5 plug fitted with a resistor) to be installed by the user.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] It is important for users to check whether their devices have automatic or switched termination, as otherwise they may end up with the DMX line being terminated multiple times or not at all when they believed it to be correct.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Additionally, terminating the DMX line often exposes physical cable faults - for example, if the "Data −" wire is broken, an unterminated DMX run may partially work, while fitting the terminator immediately exposes the problem.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Recently, wireless DMX512 adapters have become popular, especially in architectural lighting installations where cable lengths can be prohibitively long.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Such networks typically employ a wireless transmitter at the controller, with strategically placed receivers near the fixtures to convert the wireless signal back to conventional DMX512 wired network signals or wireless receivers built into the individual fixtures.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Although wireless DMX512 networks can function over distances exceeding 3,000 feet (910 m) under ideal conditions, most wireless DMX512 links are limited to a maximum distance of 1,000–1,500 feet (300–460 m) to ensure reliable operation.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The first commercially marketed wireless DMX512 system was based on frequency-hopping spread spectrum (FHSS) technology using commercial wireless modems.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Other later-generation systems still used frequency-hopping spread spectrum (FHSS) technology, but at higher bandwidth.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] FHSS systems tend to disturb other types of wireless communication systems such as WiFi/WLAN.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] This has been solved in newer wireless DMX systems by using adaptive frequency hopping, a technique to detect and avoid surrounding wireless systems, to avoid transmitting on occupied frequencies.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Multiple incompatible wireless protocols currently exist.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] While DMX-over-Ethernet protocols such as E1.31 - Streaming ACN can be used to send DMX data over WiFi, this is not generally recommended due to the highly variable latency of WiFi.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] Many alternatives to DMX512 have been proposed to address limitations such as the maximum slot count of 512 per universe, the unidirectional signal, and the lack of inherent error detection.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] The 2004 DMX512-A revision added a System Information Packet (SIP).
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] This packet can be interleaved with Null packets.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] One feature of SIPs is they allow checksums to be sent for DMX Null data.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] However, SIPs have rarely been implemented.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] E1.11-2004, a revision of DMX512-A, also lays the foundation for Remote Device Management (RDM) protocol through the definition of Enhanced Functionality.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] RDM allows for diagnostic feedback from fixtures to the controller by extending the DMX512 standard to encompass bidirectional communication between the lighting controller and lighting fixtures.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] RDM was approved by ANSI in 2006 as ANSI E1.20 and is gaining interest.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] An Ethernet-based protocol can distribute multiple DMX universes through a single cable from a control location to breakout boxes closer to fixtures.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] These boxes then output the conventional DMX512 signal.
[src:dmx512-lighting/dmx512] ANSI E1.31—2009 Entertainment Technology—Lightweight streaming protocol for transport of DMX512 using ACN, published May 4, 2009, and Art-Net are two free-to-use protocols used to achieve this.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] A **lighting control console** (also called a **lightboard**, **lighting board**, or **lighting desk**) is an electronic device used in theatrical lighting design to control multiple stage lights at once.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] They are used throughout the entertainment industry and are normally placed at the front of house (FOH) position or in a control booth.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] All lighting control consoles can control dimmers which control the intensity of conventional incandescent lights.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Many modern consoles can control Intelligent lighting (lights that can move, change colors and gobo patterns), fog machines and hazers, and other special effects devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Some consoles can also interface with other electronic performance hardware (i.e. mixing consoles, projectors, media servers, automated winches and motors, etc.) to improve synchronization or unify their control.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Lighting consoles communicate with the dimmers and other devices in the lighting system via an electronic control protocol.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The most common protocol used in the entertainment industry today is DMX512, although other protocols (e.g.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] 0-10 V analog lighting control) may still be found in use, and newer protocols such as ACN and DMX-512-A are evolving to meet the demands of ever increasing device sophistication.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Some lighting consoles can communicate over a Local IP network infrastructure to provide control over more scalable systems.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] A common protocol for this is ESTA E1.31 sACN (pronounced: streaming A.C.N.) or Art-Net.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Consoles vary in size and complexity, from small preset boards to dedicated moving light consoles.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The purpose of all lighting consoles, however is the same: to consolidate control of the lights into an organized, easy-to-use system, so that the lighting designer can concentrate on producing a good show.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Most consoles accept MIDI Show Control signals and commands to allow show control systems to integrate their capabilities into more complex shows.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Preset boards are the most basic lighting consoles—and also the most prevalent in smaller installations.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] They consist of two or more identical fader banks, called **scenes**.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The faders (control slides) on these scenes can be manually adjusted.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Each scene has the same number of channels which control the same dimmers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] So the console operator can build a scene offline or in "blind", a cross-fader or submaster is used to selectively mix or **fade** between the different scenes.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Generally, at least with a preset board, the operator has a cue sheet for each scene, which is a diagram of the board with the faders in their positions, as determined by the lighting designer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The operator sets the faders into their positions based on the cue sheets.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Typically during a cue, the operator sets the next scene.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Then the operator makes the transition between the scenes using the cross-fader.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Preset boards are not as prevalent since the advent of digital memory consoles, which can store scenes digitally, and are generally much less cumbersome but more expensive than preset boards.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] However, for small setups such as that of a DJ, they remain the board of choice for their simple to use interface and relative flexibility.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Preset boards generally control only conventional lights; though some advanced hybrid consoles can be patched to operate intelligent lights in a round-about way by setting the control channels of the light to channels the preset board can control.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] However, this is not recommended since it is a cumbersome process.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Memory-based consoles have become very popular in almost all larger installations, particularly theatres.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] This type of controller has almost completely replaced preset consoles as controllers of choice.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Memory consoles are preferable in productions where scenes do not change from show to show, such as a theatre production, because scenes are designed and digitally recorded, so there is less room for human error, and less time between lighting cues is required to produce the same result.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] They also allow for lighting cues to contain larger channel counts due to the same time savings gained from not physically moving individual channel faders.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Many memory consoles have a bank of faders.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] These faders can be programmed to control a single channel (a channel is a lighting designer's numerical name for a dimmer or group of dimmers) or a group of channels (known as a ""submaster"").
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The console may also have provision to operate in analog to a manual desk for programming scenes or live control.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] On more advanced consoles, faders can be used to control effects, chases (sequences of cues), and moving light effects (if the console can control moving lights).
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Moving Light Controllers are another step up in sophistication from Memory Consoles.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] As well as being capable of controlling ordinary luminaires via dimmers, they provide additional controls for intelligent fixtures.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] On midrange controllers, these are usually provided as a section separate from main Preset and Cue stack controls.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] These include an array of buttons allowing the operator to select the fixture or fixtures they want to control, and a joystick, or a number of wheels or rotary encoders to control fixture attributes such as the orientation (pan and tilt), focus, colour, gobos etc. found in this type of light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Unlike a fader that shows its value based on the position of a slider, a wheel is continuously variable and provides no visual feedback for the value of a particular control.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Some form of display such as LCD or LED is therefore vital for displaying this information.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The more advanced desks typically have one or more touchscreens, and present a GUI that integrates all the aspects of lighting control.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] As there is no standard way of controlling an intelligent light, an important function for this type of desk is to consolidate the various ways in which the hundreds of types of intelligent lights are controlled into a single *abstract* interface for the user.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] This frees the operator to think in terms of what they want to achieve (e.g. pan 30 degrees clockwise) instead of how it is achieved for any given fixture (e.g. send value 137 down channel 23).
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] For some further discussion on how intelligent fixtures are controlled, see Digital MultipleX (DMX).
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Personal Computer (PC) based controllers are increasing in popularity owing to portability and reduced cost.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] These lighting console solutions use software with a feature set similar to that found in a hardware-based console.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] As dimmers, automated fixtures and other standard lighting devices do not generally have current standard computer interfaces, options such as DMX-512 ports and fader/submaster panels connected via USB are commonplace.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] This system allows a "build-to-fit" approach: the end user initially provides a PC that fits their budget and any other needs with future options to improve the system, for example, by increasing the number of DMX outputs or additional console style panels.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Many lightboard vendors offer a PC software version of their consoles.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Commercial lighting control software often require a specific, and possibly expensive, hardware DMX interface.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] However, inexpensive (<$150) DMX -> USB PC interfaces such as the ENTTEC and DMXKing DMX USB Pro with public API and other DIY, and free or Open source software hardware combinations are available.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Many console vendors also make a software simulator or "offline editor" for their hardware consoles, and these are often downloadable for free.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The simulator can be used to pre-program a show, and the cues then loaded into the actual console.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] In addition, lighting visualization software is available to simulate and approximate how lighting will appear on stage, and this can be useful for programming effects and spotting obvious programming errors such as incorrect colour changes.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Many memory consoles have an optional Remote Focus Unit (RFU) controller that can be attached to the light board and used to control the board's functions (though usually in some limited capacity).
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] They are usually small enough to be handheld.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] This is ideal in situations where moving the light board is impractical, but control is needed away from where the board is located.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] That is, if the light board is in a control room that is located far from the fixtures, such as a catwalk, an RFU can be attached and an electrician or the lighting designer can bring it to a location which is close to the lights.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Some of the newer and more advanced boards have RFUs that can be connected through USB or even wirelessly.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Various manufacturers offer software for devices such as Android and iPhones that cause the devices to act as remote controllers for their consoles.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] Also, independent software developers have released applications that can send Art-Net packets from an iPhone, thus enabling an iPhone to serve as a fully featured console when used in conjunction with an Art-Net to DMX converter or Art-Net compatible luminaries and dimmers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] An example of this is ETC's (Electronic Theater Controls) app called iRFR for Apple devices or aRFR for Android devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The *Controller Interface Transport Protocol*, or *CITP*, is a network protocol used between visualizers, lighting control consoles and media servers to transport non-show critical information during pre-production.
[src:dmx512-lighting/lighting-control-console] The protocol is used for a number of purposes including SDMX, browsing media and thumbnails, and streaming media among different devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM revises the DMX512 standard to include bidirectional communication, and introduces additional options for the configuration of fixtures over the DMX512 network.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM is backwards compatible with existing DMX512 devices, and requires few changes to the physical cabling of DMX512 networks.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The RDM standard was developed by the Entertainment Services and Technology Association, and is maintained as ANSI E1.20.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] DMX512 has been the standard for the control of theatrical lighting devices, including intelligent lighting fixtures, since the mid-1990s.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] DMX512, based on the RS-485 protocol commonly used in industrial control systems, was the first universal standard for the control of stage lighting equipment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM's predecessor DMX512 is a unidirectional protocol with little capacity for error reporting or automated configuration.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] A single cable carries one "universe" of DMX512, consisting of 512 "addresses," each of which can be assigned a value from 0 to 255.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] In the earliest applications of DMX512 networks, a control console would be connected to a rack of dimmers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Within the dimmer rack, a single DMX address would control the voltage level of a single dimmer from 0% to 100%.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] In more complex applications involving intelligent lighting fixtures, a DMX address is assigned to each function of a fixture, with some fixtures utilizing blocks of addresses numbering in the dozens.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] A device's identity within the network is defined by the first address of the block it occupies, akin to a static IP address.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] In a standard DMX network, each fixture must be manually configured with a starting address, and the same starting address must be separately programmed into the control console.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM serves multiple main functions: identification, status reporting, and configuration.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Identification allows a control console to automatically detect all devices on the DMX network, distinct from their DMX address.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] This assists the operator in determining which of their devices have even powered on.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Configuration allows the control console to change the address and other properties of a device.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] This functionality avoids the time-consuming process of manually setting DMX addresses on each fixture.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Intelligent lighting fixtures often have multiple control modes and other settings, which can also be configured over RDM with the proper software support.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Status reporting from lighting fixtures enables the operator to view the status of their devices, including faults such as burnt-out lamps or failed motors.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM is enabled in many new lighting devices, and can be used in the same network as non-RDM-enabled devices, using existing cabling.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] DMX512 devices that do not support RDM should ignore all RDM commands, but in practice, some devices do malfunction when receiving RDM signals.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] DMX networks may include splitters with opto-isolator functionality, which only allow signal transmission in one direction, and filter out RDM signals.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] DMX splitters that pass through RDM signals are available, but not all splitters include this functionality.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM is a technology specific to DMX512 signals over standard twisted-pair wire.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Protocols that carry DMX signal over IP networks, such as Streaming ACN and Art-Net, have their own implementations of remote control which are backwards compatible with RDM.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The RDM protocol and the RDM physical layer were designed to be compatible with legacy equipment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] All compliant legacy DMX512 receivers should be usable in mixed systems with an RDM controller (console) and RDM responders (receivers).
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] DMX receivers and RDM responders can be used with a legacy DMX console to form a DMX512 only system.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] From a user’s point of view the system layout is very similar to a DMX system.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The controller is placed at one end of the main cable segment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The cable is run receiver to receiver in a daisy-chain fashion.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM enabled splitters are used the same way DMX splitters would be.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The far end (the non console or splitter end) of a cable segment should be terminated.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM requires two significant topology changes compared to DMX.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] However, these changes are generally internal to equipment and therefore not seen by the user.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] First, a controller’s (console’s) output is terminated.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Second, this termination must provide a bias to keep the line in the ‘marking state’ when no driver is enabled.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The reason for the additional termination is that a network segment will be driven at many points along its length.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Hence, either end of the segment, if unterminated, will cause reflections.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] A DMX console’s output drivers are always enabled.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The RDM protocol is designed so that except during discovery, there should never be data collisions.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] To ensure this lack of collisions, while making possible implementation on different platforms, there are times when all line drivers are required to be disabled.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] If nothing more than the termination was done, the line would float to some unknown level.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] In that case one or more random changes might be read on the line.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] These random changes greatly decrease system accuracy.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The standard further states that, the biasing mean “shall be polarized such that Data+ of the data link is positive with respect to Data- the data link.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The standard does not require any particular circuit for providing the basis and termination; however, the simplest method is often a passive pull apart network.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Whatever method is used must be tested with the chosen driver chip to see that the design combination still meets the requirement of E1.20.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Tests are given in Appendix F of the standard.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] These tests are for design verification and are not required as production testing.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Experience has shown many EIA485 drivers designed for 5 volt operation will pass the required tests.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] It is not so clear that all 3.3 volt parts will pass.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] In either case this performance must be verified.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Details of the pull apart network and the tests can be found in **ANSI E1.20 - 2006**.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] RDM packets are interspersed with the existing DMX data packets being used to control the lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The DMX 512 specification requires that DMX packets begin with the start code.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The default Start Code is 0x00(also known as the Null Start Code).
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] By using the start code 0xCC, RDM packets can be safely inserted between DMX data packets without older non-RDM aware devices attempting to read them.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The DMX 512 specification required DMX connectors to be a 5-pin XLR type, with only the first 3 pins being used (pins 4 and 5 were reserved for "future use").
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Unfortunately, various manufacturers started using the final two pins for various, proprietary purposes, such as low-voltage power or proprietary talk-back protocols.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] As a result, the decision was made to have all RDM communication on pins 2 and 3.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The RDM standard addresses this problem by ensuring that in all cases (except discovery) only one device is authorized to be transmitting at any given time.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Only the controller (of which there can be only one) can start an RDM exchange.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The controller will always initiate all RDM communication.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] All RDM devices have a unique identifier (UID) that consists of a manufacturer ID and serial number.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Discovery is the only situation in which data collisions can occur assuming all connected devices behave correctly.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The controller will broadcast a discovery command to all devices and await a response.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] If there are more than one device connected, the simultaneous responses will likely result in a data collision, and the controller will not receive a correctly formatted response.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The controller will then refine its search to a smaller range of UIDs according to a binary search pattern.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Once the controller receives a correct response it will attempt to mute the responding device.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] After a successful mute, the device is no longer allowed to respond to discovery messages, and the controller can continue searching for other devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Once all devices have been muted (no responses are received to discovery commands), the discovery process is finished and the controller will hold a list of all connected devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The controller will need to periodically perform searches for new devices and assert that already discovered devices are still connected.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] General communication with a specific fixture occurs in a request-response pattern.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] The controller sends the request to the device, addressing it by the device's UID.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] When the request has been sent, the controller relinquishes control of the DMX line for a given period of time, so the device can transmit its response.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] Unicast communication is the only way in which data can be retrieved from a fixture (other than its UID which can be obtained using the discovery mechanism mentioned above).
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] If the device does not respond within a given period of time, the controller can assume communication has failed, and may retry.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] To quickly send instructions to multiple fixtures, RDM allows for broadcast communication.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] This allows the controller to send an instruction to all devices, or all devices from one manufacturer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rdm-lighting] As more than one device might be receiving the message, responses are not permitted in broadcast communication except during the Discovery process.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 supports inexpensive local networks and multidrop communications links, using the same differential signaling over twisted pair as RS-422.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] It is generally accepted that RS-485 can be used with data rates up to 10 Mbit/s or, at lower speeds, distances up to 1,200 m (4,000 ft).
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] As a rule of thumb, the speed in bit/s multiplied by the length in meters should not exceed 108.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Thus a 50-meter cable should not signal faster than 2 Mbit/s.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] In contrast to RS-422, which has a driver circuit which cannot be switched off, RS-485 drivers use three-state logic allowing individual transmitters to be deactivated.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] This allows RS-485 to implement linear bus topologies using only two wires.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The equipment located along a set of RS-485 wires are interchangeably called nodes, stations or devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The recommended arrangement of the wires is as a connected series of point-to-point (multidropped) nodes, i.e. a line or bus, not a star, ring, or multiply connected network.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Star and ring topologies are not recommended because of signal reflections or excessively low or high termination impedance.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] If a star configuration is unavoidable, special RS-485 repeaters are available which bidirectionally listen for data on each span and then retransmit the data onto all other spans.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Ideally, the two ends of the cable will have a termination resistor connected across the two wires.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Without termination resistors, signal reflections off the unterminated end of the cable can cause data corruption.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Termination resistors also reduce electrical noise sensitivity due to the lower impedance.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The value of each termination resistor should be equal to the cable characteristic impedance (typically, 120 ohms for twisted pairs).
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The termination also includes pull up and pull down resistors to establish bias for each data wire for the case when the lines are not being driven by any device.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] This way, the lines will be biased to known voltages and nodes will not interpret the noise from undriven lines as actual data; without biasing resistors, the data lines float in such a way that electrical noise sensitivity is greatest when all device stations are silent or unpowered.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The EIA once labeled all its standards with the prefix RS (Recommended Standard), but the EIA/TIA officially replaced RS with EIA/TIA to help identify the origin of its standards.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The EIA has officially disbanded and the standard is now maintained by the TIA as TIA-485, but engineers and applications guides continue to use the RS-485 designation.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The initial edition of EIA RS-485 was dated April 1983.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 only specifies the electrical characteristics of the generator and the receiver: the physical layer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] It does not specify or recommend any communications protocol; Other standards define the protocols for communication over an RS-485 link.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The foreword to the standard references *The Telecommunications Systems Bulletin TSB-89* which contains application guidelines, including data signaling rate vs. cable length, stub length, and configurations.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Section 4 defines the electrical characteristics of the generator (transmitter or driver), receiver, transceiver, and system.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] These characteristics include: definition of a unit load, voltage ranges, open-circuit voltages, thresholds, and transient tolerance.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] It also defines three generator interface points (signal lines); A, B and C.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] This section also defines the logic states 1 (off) and 0 (on), by the polarity between A and B terminals.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] If A is negative with respect to B, the state is binary 1.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The reversed polarity (A positive with respect to B) is binary 0.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The standard does not assign any logic function to the two states.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485, like RS-422, can be made full-duplex by using four wires.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Since RS-485 is a multi-point specification, however, this is not necessary or desirable in many cases.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 and RS-422 can interoperate with certain restrictions.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Converters between RS-485 and RS-232 are available to allow a personal computer to communicate with remote devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] By using repeaters very large RS-485 networks can be formed.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] TSB-89A, Application Guidelines for TIA/EIA-485-A does not recommend using star topology, as doing so may lead to long stubs (branches of the star), which can cause signal reflections that make data transmission unreliable.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 does not define a communication protocol; merely an electrical interface.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Although many applications use RS-485 signal levels, the speed, format, and protocol of the data transmission are not specified by RS-485.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Interoperability of even similar devices from different manufacturers is not assured by compliance with the signal levels alone.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 signals are used in a wide range of computer and automation systems.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] In a computer system, SCSI-2 and SCSI-3 may use RS-485 to implement the physical layer for data transmission between a controller and a disk drive.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 is used for low-speed data communications in commercial aircraft cabins' vehicle bus.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] It requires minimal wiring and can share the wiring among several seats, reducing weight.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] These are used in programmable logic controllers and on factory floors.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 is used as the physical layer underlying many standard and proprietary automation protocols used to implement industrial control systems, including the most common versions of Modbus and Profibus.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] **DH 485** is a proprietary communications protocol used by Allen-Bradley in their line of industrial control units.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Utilizing a series of dedicated interface devices, it allows PCs and industrial controllers to communicate.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Since it is differential, it resists electromagnetic interference from motors and welding equipment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] In theatre and performance venues, RS-485 networks are used to control lighting and other systems using the DMX512 protocol.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 serves as a physical layer for the AES3 digital audio interconnect.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 is also used in building automation as the simple bus wiring and long cable length is ideal for joining remote devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] It may be used to control video surveillance systems or to interconnect security control panels and devices such as access control card readers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] It is also used in Digital Command Control (DCC) for model railways.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The external interface to the DCC command station is often RS-485 used by hand-held controllers or for controlling the layout in a networked PC environment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] 8P8C modular connectors are used in this case.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Because a mark (logic 1) condition is traditionally represented (e.g. in RS-232) with a negative voltage; and space (logic 0) represented with a positive one, A may be considered the *non-inverting* signal and B as inverting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The truth tables of most popular devices, starting with the SN75176, show the output signals inverted.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] These manufacturers all agree on the meaning of the standard, and their practice is in widespread use.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The issue also exists in programmable logic controller applications.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Care must be taken when using A/B naming.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 standard conformant drivers provide a differential output of a minimum 1.5 V across a 54-Ω load, whereas standard conformant receivers detect a differential input down to 200 mV.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The two values provide a sufficient margin for a reliable data transmission even under severe signal degradation across the cable and connectors.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] This robustness is the main reason why RS-485 is well suited for long-distance networking in noisy environment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] This connection may be used to limit the common-mode signal that can be impressed on the receiver inputs.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The allowable common-mode voltage is in the range −7 V to +12 V, i.e. ±7 V on top of the 0–5 V signal range.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Failure to stay within this range will result in, at best, signal corruption, and, at worst, damage to connected devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Care must be taken that an SC connection, especially over long cable runs, does not result in an attempt to connect disparate grounds together – it is wise to add some current limiting to the SC connection.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Grounds between buildings may vary by a small voltage, but with very low impedance and hence the possibility of catastrophic currents – enough to melt signal cables, PCB traces, and transceiver devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] RS-485 does not specify any connector or pinout.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] Circuits may be terminated on screw terminals, D-subminiature connectors, or other types of connectors.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The standard does not discuss cable shielding but makes some recommendations on preferred methods of interconnecting the signal reference common and equipment case grounds.
[src:dmx512-lighting/rs-485] The diagram below shows potentials of the A (blue) and B (red) pins of an RS-485 line before, during, and after transmission of one byte (0xD3, least significant bit first) of data using an asynchronous start-stop method.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The equipment used for stage lighting (e.g. cabling, dimmers, lighting instruments, controllers) are also used in other lighting applications, including corporate events, concerts, trade shows, broadcast television, film production, photographic studios, and other types of live events.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The personnel needed to install, operate, and control the equipment also cross over into these different areas of "stage lighting" applications.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The earliest known form of stage lighting occurred in Ancient Greek theaters, which were typically built outdoors and oriented so that afternoon sunlight illuminated the performance space while keeping the audience shaded.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Natural light continued to be utilized when playhouses were built with a large circular opening at the top of the theater.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] As theaters moved indoors, artificial lighting using candles and oil lamps supplemented the use of natural light via windows and shutters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Key developments in lighting technologies and practices were developed alongside the scenic stage in Italian Court Theatres by architect designers such as Bastiano da Sangallo (1481-1551), Sebastiano Serlio (1475-1554), Leone di Somi (1527-1592) and Angelo Ingegneri (1550-1613).
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Renaissance lighting techniques (including the use of darkness) were developed across Europe and detailed clearly in the writings of two architects, the Italian Nicola Sabbatini (1574-1654) and the German Joseph Furttenbach (1591-1667).
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In England following the Civil War all stage production was suspended in 1642 and no advancements were made to English theaters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] During this theatrical famine, great developments were being made in theaters on the European mainland.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Charles II, who would later become King Charles II witnessed Italian theatrical methods and brought them back to England when he came to power.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] New playhouses were built in England and their large sizes called for more elaborate lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] After the refurbishing of the theaters, it was found that the "main source of light in Restoration theaters to be chandeliers" which were "concentrated toward the front of the house, and especially over the forestage".
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] English theatres during this time used dipped candles to light chandeliers and sconces.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Dipped candles were made by dipping a wick into hot wax repeatedly to create a cylindrical candle.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Candles needed frequent trimming and relighting regardless of what was happening on-stage because "they dripped hot grease on both the audience and actors".
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Chandeliers also blocked the view of some patrons.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In the eastern world, shadow plays relied heavily on lighting to transform the story of the show because, as implied in the name, they utilized shadows to change the shapes of the characters/puppets, using the distance of the lights from the puppets to change the shape or size of the shadow.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] There were two different types of Restoration theaters in England: commercial theaters and court theaters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Commercial theaters tended to be more "conservative in their lighting, for economic reasons" and therefore used "candle-burning chandeliers" primarily.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Court theatres could afford to "use most of the Continental innovations" in their productions.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Theaters such as the Drury Lane Theatre and the Covent Garden Theatre were lit by a large central chandelier and had a varying number of smaller stage chandeliers and candle sconces around the walls of the theaters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Two main court theaters, built between 1660 and 1665, were the Cockpit Theatre and the Hall Theatre.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Chandeliers and sconces seemed to be the primary lighting sources here but other developments were being made, especially at the Hall.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] By the 1670s, the Hall Theatre started using footlights, and between 1670 and 1689 they used candles or lamps.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] It can be noted that by the end of the 17th century, "French and English stages were fairly similar".
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] There is not much written on theatrical lighting in England at the end of the 17th century and from the little information historians do have, not much changed by the middle of the 18th century.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Gas lighting began appearing in English theaters in the early 19th century including installations at Drury Lane and Covent Garden.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] These systems utilized coal gas piped through valves and pipes. that could be controlled from a gas table, an early form of centralized lighting control.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In the 1820's limelight was developed producing intense illumination by directing a flame at a cylinder of calcium oxide (quicklime) which became incandescent and emitted a bright white light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This illumination could then be directed by reflectors and lenses.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Lime light was first used for theatrical lighting at Covent garden theatre in London in 1837 and became widely adopted in theaters by the 1860's. until it was displaced by electrical lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Electric lighting began replacing gas lighting in theaters in the late nineteenth century. one of the earliest examples was the Savoy Theatre in London which in 1881 became the first theatre illuminated entirely by electric light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Early electric stage lighting systems used salt water dimmers, which controlled brightness by adjusting electrical resistance in a container of salt water these systems were widely used in theatres before modern electronic dimmers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Lighting innovations developed in English theaters during the nineteenth century helped establish many of the technologies used in modern lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Lighting design is an art form, and thus no one way is the "correct" way.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] There is a modern movement that states that the lighting design helps to create the environment in which the action takes place while supporting the style of the piece.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] "Mood" is arguable while the environment is essential.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Intensity is measured in lux, lumens and foot-candles.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Color temperature is measured in kelvins.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A light's apparent color is determined by its lamp color, the color of any gels in the optical path, its power level, and the color of the material it lights.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A tungsten lamp's color is typically controlled by inserting one or more gels (filters) into its optical path.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In the simplest case, a single gel is inserted into the optical path to produce light of the same color.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] For example, a blue gel is used to create blue light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Custom colors are obtained by means of subtractive CMY color mixing, by inserting combinations of cyan, magenta and yellow filters into the optical path of the lighting fixture.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The inserted filters may have varying densities, with correspondingly varied percentages of transmission, that *subtractively* mix colors (the filters absorb unwanted light colors, but the desired colors pass through unaffected).
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Manufacturers will sometimes include an additional green or amber ("CTO" color correction) filter to extend the range (gamut) of subtractive color mixing systems.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Lamp power also influences color in tungsten lamps.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] As the lamp power is decreased, the tungsten filament in a bulb will tend to produce increasing percentages of orange light, as compared to the nearly white light emitted at full power.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This is known as *amber shift* or *amber drift*.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Thus a 1000-watt instrument at 50 percent power will emit a higher percentage of orange light than a 500-watt instrument operating at full power.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] LED fixtures create color through additive color mixing with red, green, blue, and in some cases amber, LEDs at different intensities.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This type of color mixing is often used with borderlights and cyclorama lights.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Direction refers to the shape, quality and evenness of a lamp's output.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The pattern of light an instrument makes is largely determined by three factors.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The first are the specifics of the lamp, reflector and lens assembly.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Different mounting positions for the lamp (axial, base up, base down), different sizes and shapes of reflector and the nature of the lens (or lenses) being used can all affect the pattern of light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Secondly, the specifics of how the lamp is focused affect its pattern.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In *ellipsoidal reflector spotlights (ERS)* or *profile spotlights*, there are two beams of light emitted from the lamp.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] When the cones of both intersect at the throw distance (the distance to the stage), the lamp has a sharply defined 'hard' edge.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] When the two cones do not intersect at that distance, the edge is fuzzy and 'soft'.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Depending on which beam (direct or reflected) is outside the other, the pattern may be 'thin and soft' or 'fat and soft'.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Lastly, a gobo or break up pattern may be applied to ERSs and similar instruments.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This is typically a thin sheet of metal with a shape cut into it.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] It is inserted into the instrument near its aperture.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Gobos, or templates, come in many shapes, but often include leaves, waves, stars and similar patterns.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The focus is where an instrument is pointed.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The final focus should place the "hot spot" of the beam at the actor's head level when standing at the center of the instrument's assigned "focus area" on the stage.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Position refers to the location of an instrument in the theater's fly system or on permanent pipes in front-of-house locations.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Hanging is the act of placing the instrument in its assigned position.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In addition to these, certain modern instruments are automated, referring to motorized movement of either the entire fixture body or the movement of a mirror placed in front of its outermost lens.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] These fixtures and the more traditional follow spots add direction and motion to the relevant characteristics of light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Automated fixtures fall into either the "moving head" or "moving mirror/scanner" category.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Scanners have a body which contains the lamp, circuit boards, transformer, and effects (color, gobo, iris etc.) devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A mirror is panned and tilted in the desired position by pan and tilt motors, thereby causing the light beam to move.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Moving head fixtures have the effects and lamp assembly inside the head with transformers and other electronics in the base or external ballast.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] There are advantages and disadvantages to both.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Scanners are typically faster and less costly than moving head units but have a narrower range of movement.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Moving head fixtures have a much larger range of movement as well as a more natural inertial movement but are typically more expensive.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The above characteristics are not always static, and it is frequently the variation in these characteristics that is used in achieving the goals of lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Stanley McCandless was perhaps the first to define controllable qualities of light used in theater.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In *A Method for Lighting the Stage*, McCandless discusses *color*, *distribution*, *intensity* and *movement* as the qualities that can be manipulated by a lighting designer to achieve the desired visual, emotional and thematic look on stage.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The McCandless method, outlined in that book, is widely embraced today.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The method involves lighting an object on the stage from three angles—2 lights at 45 degrees to the left and right, and one at 90 degrees (perpendicular to the front of the object).
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] An alternative formulation is by Jody Briggs, who calls them *Variable of Light*: Angle, Color, Intensity, Distance, Texture, Edge-quality, Size, and Shape.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A lighting designer (LD) is familiar with the various types of lighting instruments and their uses.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The schedule is a list of all required lighting equipment, including color gel, gobos, color wheels, barndoors and other accessories.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The light plot is typically a plan view of the theatre where the performance will take place, with every luminaire marked.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This typically specifies the approximate lighting focus and direction, a reference number, accessories, the address number (assigned DMX addresses) in the dimmer system and channel on the lighting control console.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A lighting designer must satisfy the requirements set forth by the director or head planner.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Practical experience is required to know the effective use of different lighting instruments and color in creating a design.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Many designers start their careers as lighting technicians.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Often, this is followed by training in a vocational college or university that offers theatre courses.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Many jobs in larger venues and productions require a degree from a vocational school or college in theatrical lighting, or at least a bachelor's degree.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In the context of lighting design, a lighting instrument (also called a *luminaire* or *lantern*) is a device that produces controlled lighting as part of the effects a lighting designer brings to a show.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The term *lighting instrument* is preferred to *light* to avoid confusion between light and light sources.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] There are a variety of instruments frequently used in the theater.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Additional features will vary depending on the exact type of fixture.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Most theatrical light bulbs (or *lamps*, the term usually preferred) are tungsten-halogen (or quartz-halogen), an improvement on the original incandescent design that uses a halogen gas instead of an inert gas to increase lamp life and output.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Fluorescent lights are infrequently used other than as worklights because, although they are far more efficient, they are expensive to make *dimmed* (run at less than full power) without using specialised dimmer ballasts and only very expensive models will dim to very low levels.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] They also do not produce light from a single point or easily concentrated area, and usually have a warm-up period, during which they emit no light or do so intermittently.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] However, fluorescent lights are being used more and more for special effects lighting in theaters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] High-intensity discharge lamps (or HID lamps), however, are now common where a very bright light output is required—for example in large follow spots, hydrargyrum medium-arc iodide (HMI) floods, and modern automated fixtures.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] When dimming is required, it is done by mechanical dousers or shutters, as these types of lamps also cannot be electrically dimmed.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Since the early 2000's, LED (Light emitting diode) Instruments has become increasingly common in theatre and concert production.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] LED fixtures consume less energy than traditional incandescent or halogen lamps and can produce a wide range of colors without the need for gel filters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Most instruments are suspended or supported by a U-shaped *yoke*, or 'trunnion arm' fixed to the sides of the instrument, normally near its center of gravity.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] On the end of such, a clamp (known as a hook-clamp, C-clamp, or pipe clamp—pipe referring to battens) is normally fixed, made in a "C" configuration with a screw to lock the instrument onto the pipe or batten from which it is typically hung.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Once secured, the fixture can be panned and tilted using tension adjustment knobs on the yoke and clamp.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] An adjustable c-wrench, ratchet (US) or spanner (UK) is often used to assist the technician in adjusting the fixture.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Most venues require an additional metal safety cable or chain to be attached between the fixture and its truss, or other string support anchorage.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Some larger fixtures can weigh over 100 lb (45 kg) and are suspended very high above performers heads, and could cause serious injury or death if they fell by accident or due to incorrect attachment.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In the event of failure, the cable would halt the fall of the fixture before it could cause serious damage or injury.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Many venues place strict guidelines regarding the use of safety cables.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The entire lighting apparatus includes the lights themselves, the physical structure which supports them, the cabling, control systems, dimmers, power supplies, and the light boards.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Hanging the lights or hanging the battons to hang the lights is known as 'rigging'.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] All lights are loosely classified as either *floodlights* (wash lights) or *spotlights*.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The distinction has to do with the degree to which one is able to control the shape and quality of the light produced by the instrument, with spotlights being controllable, sometimes to an extremely precise degree, and floodlights being completely uncontrollable.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Instruments that fall somewhere in the middle of the spectrum can be classified as either a spot or a flood, depending on the type of instrument and how it is used.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In general, spotlights have lenses while floodlights are lensless, although this is not always the case.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Within the groups of "wash" and "spot" light, there are other, more specific types of fixtures.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This nomenclature also changes across the world depending on location and industry.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] These fixtures feature a compound lens which allows the designer to place obstructions within the image path which are then projected.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] These obstructions could be "gobos" or shutters.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A profile is a spot light, but allows for precise focusing.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] , founders of Century Lighting, in 1933.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] it features as the final optical device within the chain.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Traditionally theatre and stage lighting has been of the "generic" type.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] These are lights which are focussed, geled, and then simply dimmed to give the effect the designer wants.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In recent years the emergence of moving lights (or automated lights) has had a substantial impact of theatre and stage lighting.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A typical moving light allows the designer to control the position, color, shape, size and strobing of the light beam created.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This can be used for exciting effects for the entertainment or dancefloor use.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Moving lights are also often used instead of having a large number of "generic" lights.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] This is because one moving light can do the work of several generics.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In Australia and many other places, the lamps inside a theatrical fixture are referred to as *bubbles*.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In North American English, a bubble refers to the protrusion that occurs when one's body (or other oily substance) contacts the lamp.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Heat will cause the portion of the lamp which has oil on it to expand when it is on creating the bubble, and causing the lamp to explode.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] That is why one should never directly touch the glass portion of a lamp.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Cleaning with rubbing alcohol will remove the oil.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Lighting control tools might best be described as anything that changes the quality of the light.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Historically this has been done by the use of intensity control.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Technological advancements have made intensity control relatively simple - solid state dimmers are controlled by one or more lighting controllers.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Controllers are commonly lighting consoles designed for sophisticated control over very large numbers of dimmers or luminaires, but may be simpler devices which play back stored sequences of lighting states with minimal user interfaces.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Consoles are also referred to as lighting desks or light-boards.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The lighting controller is connected to the dimmers (or directly to automated luminaires) using a control cable or wireless link (e.g.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] DMX512) or network, allowing the dimmers which are bulky, hot and sometimes noisy, to be positioned away from the stage and audience and allowing automated luminaires to be positioned wherever necessary.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] These allow the possibility of feedback of position, state or fault conditions from units, whilst allowing much more detailed control of them.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] A dimmer is a device used to vary the average voltage applied to an instrument's lamp.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The brightness of a lamp depends on its electric current, which in turn depends on the applied lamp voltage.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] When the applied voltage is decreased, a lamp's electric current will also decrease, thus reducing the light output from the lamp (dimming it).
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Conversely, a higher voltage will cause higher lamp current and increased (brighter) light output.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Dimmers are frequently found in large enclosures called *racks* or *dimmer racks* that draw significant three-phase power.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] They are often removable modules that range from 20-ampere, 2.4-kilowatt to 100-ampere units.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In the case of incandescent lamps, some color changes occur as a lamp is dimmed, allowing for a limited amount of color control through a dimmer.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Fades (brightness transitions) can be either UP or DOWN, meaning that the light output is increasing or decreasing during the transition.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Most modern dimmers are solid state, though many mechanical dimmers are still in operation.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] In many cases, a dimmer can be replaced by a *constant power module* (CPM), which is typically a 20- or 50-ampere breaker in a dimming module casing.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] CPMs are used to supply line voltage to non-dimming electrical devices such as smoke machines, chain winches, and scenic motors that require constant operating voltage.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] When a device is powered by a CPM, it is fully energized whenever the CPM is turned on, independent of lighting console levels.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] CPMs must be used (in lieu of dimmers) to power non-dimming devices that require specific line voltages (e.g. in the US, 120 V, 60 Hz power) in order to avoid damage to such devices.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Dimmers are seldom used to control non-dimming devices because even if a dimmer channel is trusted to always operate at full power, it may not be controlled when communications are disrupted by start up and shut down of the lighting control surface, noise interference, or DMX disconnects or failure.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Such a loss of control might cause a dimmer to dim a circuit and thus potentially damage its non-dimming device.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Devices like moving heads also require independent power, as they cannot function on a partially dimmed channel for power, on top of requiring several other channels in order to convey all of the data they require for their several features.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Fixtures may also incorporate smoke machines, snow machines, haze machines etc., allowing many special effects to be run from a single desk.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Increasingly, modern lighting instruments are available which allow remote control of effects other than light intensity, including direction, color, beam shape, projected image, and beam angle.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] The ability to move an instrument ever more quickly and quietly is an industry goal.
[src:dmx512-lighting/stage-lighting] Some automated lights have built-in dimming and so are connected directly to the control cable or network and are independent of external dimmers.
